<html>
<title>CAPRICORN RECORDS GOES TO POT</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">
<p>
<h2>CAPRICORN RECORDS<br>
GOES TO POT</h2>
<hr size = 3 width = 50%>
<p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>David J. Chamberlin and Robert L. Maginnis</i></center>
<p>
Unfazed by the hit that Time Warner has received in the last two
months for peddling sex, drugs, and violence, Capricorn Records
will soon release <I>Hempilation</I>, a benefit album with a portion
of the proceeds going to the National Organization for the Reform
of Marijuana Laws (NORML).
<P>
It is not surprising that pro-drug musicians support NORML  --
 at least 45 bands have declared their support for legalizing
marijuana.[1]  It is surprising however, that Capricorn Records'
president Phil Walden didn't learn from Time Warner's recent public
flogging over the promoting of music that glorifies drug use,
puts down women, promotes Satanism, or encourages violence.
<P>
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala recently emphasized
the dangers of marijuana, saying,  &quot;Young people must understand
that there is clear scientific evidence that marijuana is a dangerous
drug that can have acute and hazardous effects. . .Drug use --
 including marijuana. . .is unwise, unhealthful, illegal and wrong.&quot;[2]
<P>
The short-term effects of marijuana include impairment in learning
and memory, perception, judgment and complex motor skills.  Marijuana
can cause difficulty in speaking, listening effectively, thinking,
retaining knowledge, problem solving, and forming concepts.[3]
<P>
More than 10,500 published scientific papers show that marijuana
damages brain cells and the lungs, may adversely affect reproduction
in women and fertility in men, endangers the unborn baby and newborns
of pot-smoking women, and could damage the heart.[4]
<P>
The effects of unabated illicit drug use go beyond those already
outlined.  For example, illicit drug use correlates with crime.
 The Bureau of Justice Statistics found that 32 percent of inmates
have used cocaine and that half had used drugs in the month before
their offense.  Seventy-five percent reported having used marijuana
in the past.[5]
<P>
Drugs numb the conscience and lower inhibitions.  They contribute
to mood disorders, depression, and low self esteem.  A high proportion
of cocaine users admit the drug makes them feel violent at times.
<P>
Consider some recent examples of youth violence that involved
drug abuse.  
<UL>
<LI>Five Dodge City, Kansas teenagers, high on marijuana, killed
a stranger for no obvious reason.[6]
<P>
<LI>Three West Palm Beach, Florida teenagers mixed beer, rum,
marijuana and cocaine and then kidnapped and set ablaze a tourist
from Brooklyn.[7]
<P>
<LI>A New Scandia Township, Minnesota teen shot his mother and
stepfather to death.  He admitted to almost daily abuse of marijuana.[8]
<P>
<LI>Two Miami, Florida teenagers were smoking marijuana when one
accidentally shot and killed the other.[9]</UL>
<P>
Not all users become violent, but social scientists confirm the
relationship between drug use and juvenile delinquency.  A 1990
study published in the <I>Journal of Drug Issues</I> found the
strongest association between the severity of the crime and the
type of substance abused  --  the more intoxicating the substance,
the more serious the incident.[10]
<P>
A study in <I>Today's Delinquent</I> found alcohol and marijuana
users commit twice the number of delinquent acts as non-users,
and a study in <I>Adolescence</I> found that half of all polydrug
users had engaged in delinquent acts.[11]
<P>
Fortunately, Walden still has time before <I>Hempilation's</I>
Sept. 26 release to reverse his blatant pro-drug decision.  Capricorn
ought to follow Simon &amp; Schuster's example of five years ago,
when it canceled plans to publish <I>American Psycho</I>, a novel
by Bret Easton Ellis, after advance complaints about objectionable
passages detailing the sexual torture and mutilation of women.[12]
<P>
It's time that record companies meet their responsibility to distribute
music that doesn't glorify drug use.  It's time Capricorn Records
heeded the timely warning that Time Warner received from angry
parents.
<P>
<center>***</center>
<P>
<I>David J. Chamberlin is the Special Assistant to the Vice President
for Policy and Robert L. Maginnis is a policy analyst at the Family
Research Council, a Washington, DC-based research and advocacy
organization. </I>
<p><hr><p>
