<html>
<title>SEX EDUCATION: WHAT WORKS?</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">
<p>
<h2>SEX EDUCATION: WHAT WORKS?</h2></center>
<hr size = 3 width = 50%>
<p>
The institutionalization of &quot;family life&quot; or sex education
classes in public and private schools around the country has created
a demand for curricula on the subject.  Unfortunately, the broad
reach of organizations such as Planned Parenthood and SIECUS has
left many school boards and parents thinking that there is no
alternative except to teach &quot;safe sex.&quot;  But there <I>is</I>
an alternative that has shown to be even more effective than &quot;safe
sex&quot; in reducing teen pregnancy and sexually-transmitted
diseases -- abstinence.  This paper is designed to help concerned
school board members and parents choose a solid abstinence curriculum.
<p>
<center><h3>WHY ABSTINENCE EDUCATION?</h3></center>
<p>
Abstinence is the only strategy for preventing teenage pregnancy
and sexually-transmitted diseases that is 100 percent effective.
 According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
it is &quot;the most effective solution&quot; to unwanted pregnancy
and sexual disease.[1]
<p>
Given the effectiveness of abstinence, a number of states -- including
Texas, California, Washington, Pennsylvania, Illinois, and Indiana -- have
passed laws in recent years stipulating that public school sex
education programs be abstinence-based.[2] Many of these programs
have produced promising results:
<p><ul>
<li>San Marcos Junior High in San Marcos, California, adopted
an abstinence-only curriculum developed by Teen-Aid, Inc., titled
<I>Sexuality, Commitment, and Family</I>.  The year before the
curriculum was implemented, 147 girls were reported pregnant.
 But two years after the program's adoption, only 20 girls became
pregnant.[3]
<p>
<li>Historically, the eighth-grade class at Nathan Hale Middle
School in the Chicago suburb of Crestwood included a number of
already pregnant girls. When the school decided to adopt an abstinence
program for the kids, many adults were skeptical.  But after three
years of quality sessions with the abstinence program <I>Project
Taking Charge</I>, the school graduated three pregnancy-free classes
in a row.[4]
<p>
<li>In the Washington, D.C. chapter of &quot;Best Friends,&quot;
only one out of 400 girls has become pregnant since the program
began.  Elayne Bennett, director of &quot;Best Friends,&quot; says that 
between 20 and 70 pregnancies are common
for the same-sized group of fifth- to ninth-grade girls in the
District of Columbia.  One &quot;Best Friends&quot; member explains,
&quot;I want to save my virginity for the man I marry....And I
want my child to have a daddy.&quot;[5]
<p>
<li>An evaluation of the abstinence-based program <I>Sex Respect:
 The Option of True Sexual Freedom</I> found that students participating
in the program had considerably lower pregnancy rates than those
in a comparison group.  Only 5 percent of the female program participants
and 9 percent of the non-program students became pregnant in the
two years following the program.[6]
<p>
<li>Emory University's abstinence-only curriculum, <I>Postponing
Sexual Involvement</I>, teaches kids about abstinence through
skill-building exercises on &quot;how to say no.&quot;  An evaluation
of the program showed that its participants were less likely to
become sexually active than those not involved in the program.[7]
<p>
<li><I>AANCHOR</I>, an alternative national curriculum on responsibility,
stresses the importance of family involvement and individual responsibility
to prevent adolescent pregnancy.  An evaluation of the curriculum
found three statistically significant differences between students
receiving the AANCHOR curriculum and students receiving the standard
school curriculum. The students participating in AANCHOR were
significantly more likely to report (1) higher family strengths,
i.e., loyalty, emotional support, cohesion, (2) greater discussions
with parents about sexual values and beliefs, and (3) more abstinent
attitudes regarding premarital sexual involvement.[8]
<p>
<li>Students who participated in the abstinence-based <I>FACTS</I>
curriculum showed significant pre-post effects occurring on the
measures of (1) affirmation of abstinence, (2) rejection of permissiveness,
and (3) future orientation and peer support for abstinence.  These
attitudinal data are important indicators of delaying sexual activity.[9]
</ul><p>
<center><h3>HOW TO CHOOSE A GOOD ABSTINENCE CURRICULUM</h3></center>
<p>
In order to choose an appropriate abstinence curriculum, parents
and school board members should study curricula for their focus,
methodologies, and content.
<p>
<b>Focus of Curricula:</b> The growing interest in abstinence
curriculum has caused many contraception programs to frame themselves
as &quot;abstinence-based,&quot; &quot;abstinence-plus&quot; or
&quot;comprehensive&quot; because they mention abstinence as one
of several options.  Such programs, however, communicate a mixed
message to students which thereby tremendously weakens the abstinence
message.  Some common characteristics of these &quot;comprehensive&quot;
or &quot;abstinence-plus&quot; programs are that they (1) assume
that teenagers are inevitably sexually active, (2) emphasize contraception
and abortion, and (3) include affective decision-making (presenting
abstinence as one of many options from which to choose).  Thus,
parents and school boards should choose a curriculum that avoids
these danger points, and instead upholds abstinence as the way
to handle teen sex issues.
<p>
<b>Methodology of Curricula:</b> The method used to deliver sex
education material heavily influences the way students will respond
to the abstinence message.  Effective abstinence programs are
directive in their approach.  Dr. Onalee McGraw provides a comparative
analysis of competing delivery models of sex education in her
book <i>Foundations for Family Life Education</i>:[10]
<p><hr><p>
<pre width=132>
<center><B>Directive</B>                              <B> Non-Directive</B></center>

Abstinence is defined as a positive     Abstinence is taught within the         
lifestyle that promotes self-control.   context of contraceptive options.       

Sexual rights and responsibilities are  Sexual rights and responsibilities are  
not merely personal; they are linked    grounded in the right of the            
to society's needs and a moral code.    supposedly &quot;autonomous&quot; individual to   
                                        choose those actions that are right     
                                        for him or her based on personally      
                                        chosen values and classroom             
                                        information.                            

Core values are taught as objectively   Core values are taught as essentially   
true and good.                          subjective.                             

Parental guidance is essential.         Only a minority of parents are willing  
                                        to guide their children.                

Teacher is role model and leader;       Teacher serves as a facilitator to      
provides clear principles and           provide information and manage the      
guidance.                               group process in the classroom.         

All children need positive rationale    Children are becoming sexually active   
for pre-marital abstinence and high     earlier and nothing can be done to      
expectations from adults to form        prevent this.                           
abstinent values.                                                               
</pre>
<p><hr><p>
Directive abstinence education emphasizes the importance of values
and attitudes, which is consistent with a U.S. Department of Education
study, &quot;The Role of Responsibility and Knowledge in Reducing
Teenage Out-of-Wedlock Childbearing,&quot; which found that &quot;adolescents
with strong feelings of control over their lives, with higher
educational expectations, and with parents who show concern and
have higher educational expectations for their daughters have
lower chances of experiencing teenage childbirth.&quot;[11]
<p>
Furthermore, students want help in saying &quot;no&quot; to sexual
activity.  When Emory University surveyed 1,000 sexually active
girls and asked them what they would most like to learn to reduce
teen pregnancy, 84 percent responded, &quot;How to say no without
hurting the other person's feelings.&quot;[12]  Moreover, a recent
study done by Roper Starch in association with the Sex Information
and Education Council of the United States (SIECUS) found that,
of the teens who have had sex, 54 percent wish they would have
waited until they were older.[13]
<p>
<b>Content of Curricula:</b> Sex education curricula vary greatly
by content, and parents should be particularly concerned if the
curriculum contains information or pictures too explicit for the
intended audience.  Caution is recommended even in cases in which
a particular sex education curriculum is widely used or endorsed
by prominent organizations.  For example:
<ul><p>
<li>The two-million member National Education Association (NEA)
endorses sex education programs that promote birth control and
homosexuality.[14]
<p>
<li>The influential Sex Information and Education Council of the
United States (SIECUS) has published a widely used set of goals
for sex education curricula entitled, &quot;<U>Guidelines for
Comprehensive Sexuality Education:  Kindergarten - 12th Grade</U>&quot;.
 The report promotes abortion, unmarried couples living together,
and homosexual relationships as equal to heterosexual relationships.[15]
</ul><p>
<b>References:</b> For more information on selecting a solid
sex education curriculum, see the Addendum on &quot;Abstinence-Based
Sex Education Resources.&quot;
<p>
-- 11/6/95
<p><hr><p>
