<html>
<title>CAN GOALS 2000 BE FIXED?</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">
<p>
<h2>CAN GOALS 2000 BE FIXED?</h2></center>
<hr size = 3 width = 50%>
<p>
Goals 2000 proponents are conceding flaws in their prized program.
President Bill Clinton himself recently confided to writer Ben
Wattenberg that his education program wasn't what he had hoped
it would be.
<p>
Nevertheless, Goals 2000 spin doctors are now suggesting that,
with the right makeover, the program will emerge irresistible
even to those who previously spurned it.  So they're willing to
undergo an utterly painless procedure:  removal of two controversial
surface elements of Goals 2000 -- the National Education Standards
and Improvement Council (NESIC), and opportunity-to-learn standards.
<p>
<h4>Leaders in the U.S. Congress, governors' offices and state
legislatures should understand that lifts and tucks aren't enough.
The core elements of Goals 2000 are unacceptable:</h4>
<p><ul>
<li>National Education Goals written as federal law (Public Law
103-227); 
<li>a federally funded National Education Goals Panel;
<li>a federally funded National Education Standards and Improvement
Council (NESIC);
<li>a new formula for reform:  federally funded standards and
assessments; and
<li>a prescription that states use this formula for reform and
submit their standards and assessments to the federal government
for approval.
</ul><p>
Never before have states had to submit their &quot;lesson plans&quot;
to get federal money.  When the U.S. Education Department was
created back in 1979, it was prohibited from dealing with curricular
issues.  Standards and assessments are curricular matters, and
the federal government has no business formulating or reviewing
them.
<p>
<h4>New Twist:  A Dangerous Liaison</h4>
<p>
Some officials, however, have no problem with federal review of
state plans -- in fact, they extend the offer to local districts
as well.  They propose that the federal government disregard the
authority of states like Virginia, New Hampshire, Montana and
Alabama, which have chosen not to participate in Goals 2000, and
go straight to the local districts interested in making a few
bucks by hitching up with Goals 2000.  What better way to invite
federal intrusion into local schools than to have local districts
bypass state authority and submit their plans directly to the
federal government for approval?
<p>
Goals 2000 is built on the flawed thesis that a greater federal
role in the education system will improve schools.  It hasn't
and it won't.  The program and the systems it spawned should be
discontinued immediately.  The money freed up will be spent more
effectively on real education needs -- not systems management
-- if left in the hands of parents and teachers closest to the
student.
<p>
-- 12/1/95

<p>

