<HTML>
<TITLE> FEDERAL GOVERNMENT USES</TITLE>
<BODY>
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<P>
<H2> FEDERAL GOVERNMENT USES<BR>
 TAXPAYER MONEY TO PROMOTE<BR>
 FEMINIST AGENDA</H2>
</CENTER>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 50%>
<P>
<CENTER>
<I>by</I>
<P>
<I> Robert L. Maginnis</I></CENTER>
<P>
The federal government used taxpayer money to buy packets of radical
feminist literature that denigrates men, promotes abortion on
demand, and declares homosexuality to be the moral equivalent
of heterosexuality.
<P>
The Postal Service and the United States Information Agency have
purchased these packets from the feminist Ms. Foundation for Women
and distributed them nationwide.  The materials were designed
to help plan the annual &quot;Take Our Daughters to Work Day,&quot;
which occurred Thursday, April 27th.  
<P>
The Ms. material:
<P>
<LI> Demonizes men and makes girls appear to be uniformly victimized
in a patriarchal society.
<P>
<LI> Presents an unbalanced analysis of educational opportunities
for the sexes.
<P>
<LI>Promotes abortion and warns that unnamed factions want to take
away the &quot;right to choose.&quot;
<P>
<LI> Severely exaggerates statistics.
<P>
The 136-page packets include parent, employer and school guides;
lesson plans for girls and boys; a synopsis of gender bias research;
and merchandise and literature order forms.  
<P>
The Ms. Foundation claims responsibility for creating and sponsoring
&quot;Take Our Daughters to Work Day&quot; as a public-education
campaign about girls and self-esteem.  According to its mission
statement, the Ms. Foundation &quot;directs resources to break
down barriers based on ...sexual orientation...[and promotes]
reproductive rights.&quot;  &quot;Sexual orientation&quot; is
code for homosexuality.
<P>
The packets include books such as <U><I>Medicine Women</I></U>,
for girls age 13 and up, which teaches about women who were midwives,
witches, high priestesses, female warriors and more.  Another
book, <U><I>Reinventing the Family: the Emerging Story of Lesbian
and Gay Parents</I></U> &quot;dramatize[s] the ingrained antipathy
of the larger society toward homosexuals [and] refute[s] the
detrimental assumptions hampering wider acceptance of gay parenting.&quot;

<P>
The packet further profiles facts about &quot;male dominance,&quot;
e.g., &quot;Between 1980 and 1990, the number of senior girls
in high school interested in engineering dropped by 25%.  Nationally,
the number of college women going into science and graduating
in science is declining.  Women and girls continue to be enrolled
in education and training programs that prepare them for low-wage
jobs in traditionally female occupations.&quot;
<P>
The materials often lack balance.  For example,  no mention is
made that more bachelor's and master's degrees are awarded to
women; boys get better scores in math and science, but girls get
higher scores in reading and writing; boys in eighth grade are
50 percent more likely to be held back a grade; and boys in high
school constitute 68 percent of the &quot;special education&quot;
population.
<P>
Feminist heroines like professor Anita Hill, Planned Parenthood
founder Margaret Sanger and activist Gloria Steinem are highlighted,
as are events like the Supreme Court decision, <I>Roe v. Wade</I>,
which legalized abortion.
<P>
Anita Hill is accorded &quot;victim&quot; status in the Clarence
Thomas Supreme Court confirmation hearing because she testified
&quot;before an all-male, all-white Senate judiciary committee.&quot;
<P>
Ms. Founder Gloria Steinem is credited with the statement: &quot;A
woman without a man is like a fish without a bicycle.&quot;  What
does this have to do with the self-esteem of little girls?
<P>
The pro-abortion message is clear.  Under the name of Margaret
Sanger the material reads: &quot;Still, in the 90s, 40,000 teenage
girls drop out of school each year because of pregnancy.&quot;
 Next to <I>Roe v. Wade</I>: an &quot;estimated 1.2 million additional
unintended pregnancies would occur each year in absence of publicly
funded women's health services.&quot;
<P>
The material also includes the statement: &quot;10% of American
women are lesbians and approximately 3.5 million lesbian and gay
Americans have had children.&quot;  The 10% figure is based on
Alfred Kinsey's thoroughly discredited estimate of the incidence
of homosexuality in the population.  Kinsey, an Indiana University
zoologist who authored <U><I>Sexual Behavior in the Human Male</I></U>
in 1948, based his research on 12,000 interviews, relying heavily
on data gleaned from criminals.  He extrapolated his findings
to the general population.  A number of recent studies have found
the population indulging in homosexual behavior to be considerably
less than 10 percent, and probably no more than 1 to 2 percent.
 
<P>
In a blatant attempt to redefine the family, the material lists
an unknown court case that declared &quot;[t]wo women make up
a `family of affinity.'&quot;  Also, the wildly exaggerated estimate
that 3.5 million children are being raised in homosexual homes
has no foundation in fact.
<P>
On another &quot;hot&quot; feminist issue, the Ms. Foundation
claims that &quot;Every 15 seconds in the U.S. a woman is battered.
 It is the greatest single cause of injury to women, more than
car accidents, muggings and rapes combined.&quot;  This, too,
is an exaggeration.
<P>
There are 31,536,000 seconds in a year.  If an American woman
is battered every 15 seconds then there are 2,124,000 such incidents.
 According to the Justice Department there are only 133,228 single-offender
assaults each year attributed to an offending spouse.  That's
one every 237 seconds.  
<P>
The Justice Department's 1994 report, &quot;Violence Against Women,&quot;
found that women are almost twice as likely to be victimized by
a boyfriend or ex-spouse than by a current spouse.  It projects
each year that there are 367,462 assaults by boyfriends or ex-spouses
compared to 195,980 by spouses.  And women are more likely to
be assaulted by a friend than by an intimate or relative.
<P>
Although the Ms. Foundation claims that &quot;girls are 4 to 5
times more likely to attempt suicide,&quot;  it neglects to mention
that boys actually kill themselves at a rate six times that of
girls.
<P>
The Census Bureau found that for all Americans 15 to 24 years
old in 1991, 11.8 percent of boys and 9.8 percent of girls used
cigarettes.  But Ms. says, &quot;Girls smoke more than boys.&quot;
<P>
While the feminist organization claims that girls are neglected
in classrooms, the fact is that most of the attention boys receive
is disciplinary.  Factoring-out conduct-related exchanges makes
the numbers similar.
<P>
The Ms. Foundation is a highly partisan political advocacy organization
which relies on unvetted research.  Ms. literature routinely has
promoted division between the sexes and has denigrated women who
do not work outside the home.  The federal government should not
embrace -- and thereby endorse -- materials which are anti-male,
pro-abortion, and pro-homosexual.  
<P>
 <CENTER>***</CENTER>
<P>
<I>Robert Maginnis is a policy analyst with the Family Research
Council, a Washington, DC-based research and advocacy organization.</I>

<p>

