<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>DRUG BROCHURE></TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<IMG SRC="abandon.jpg">
</P>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD col width=400 valign=top><blockquote>
<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<IMG SRC="defense.jpg"><br>
<Font Size="1">Source:  Office of National Drug Control Policy, 1996.</font>
<P>
<center><font size="1"><I>"I have been in Congress over two decades, and I have<br>
never, never, never found any administration thats been so<br>
silent on this great challenge [drugs] to the American people."</I><br>
                              -Representative Charles Rangel, 1994</font><br>
</center>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>  During the first days of the new administration in 1993, the Drug Czars office was slashed by over 80 percent.
<LI>  Between 1993 and 1995, 227 Drug Enforcement Administration agent positions were cut, weakening the front lines in the war on drugs.
</UL></blockquote></td>
<td col width=400 valign=top><blockquote><UL>
<LI>  Federal drug-related case filings declined by 10.3 percent between FYs 1992 and 1995, while the number of cases refused for prosecution by the Justice Department rose by 18.6 percent.
<LI>  Drugs are cheaper and more plentiful on American streets since 1993  largely the result of slashed interdiction efforts.
<LI>  Marijuana eradication has dropped by 59 percent since 1992.
<LI>  While federal funding for drug treatment increased by 108 percent between FYs 1989 and 1994, the number of people treated increased by only 17 percent.
<LI>  Drug treatment centers are currently being used at only 75 percent of capacity.
<LI>  Too many recently appointed federal judges have been exceedingly lenient toward drug offenders.  Further expansion of criminal rights would undermine the work of law enforcement and put the public at even greater risk.
</UL>
<P>
<P> <center>
<font size="1"><I>"A strategy . . .is only as good as the resources that follow it<br>
and the visible leadership that advances it."</I></center><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>--James Copple
National Director, Community
Anti-Drug Coalitions of America</blockquote></blockquote></font>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
<p align=center>
<img src="crisis.jpg"></p>
<TABLE>
<tr><td col width=400 valign=top><blockquote>
<center><font size="1"><I>"Drug use is wrong because it is immoral and it is immoral<br>
because it enslaves the mind and destroys the soul."<br></I></center>
<blockquote><blockquote>--James Q. Wilson</font></blockquote></blockquote>
<P>
The skyrocketing increase in the use of illegal drugs has been accompanied by a softening of attitudes toward drug abuse.  A clear, moral appeal to "Just Say No" has been replaced with mixed messages of tolerance and moral ambivalence toward drug use.  This ambivalence can be seen in both the White House and the schoolhouse:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>  Teen attitudes towards drug use have softened significantly since 1992.
<LI>  The non-partisan Partnership for a Drug-Free America concluded, "Todays teens are less likely to consider drug use harmful and risky, more likely to believe that drug use is widespread and tolerated, and feel more pressure to try illegal drugs than they did just tow years ago."
</UL></blockquote></td>
<td col width=400 valign=top><blockquote>
<UL>
<LI>  Despite the surge in drug use, little has been said by the national government about the dangers of drug use.  Studies show that during the first nine months of 1995, out of more than 1000 interviews, statements, remarks and proclamations, the President mentioned drugs only 18 times.  As a recent <I>Newsweek</I> article reported:  "It is simply beyond argument that Bill clinton has failed to use the power of his office to lead the war on drugs."
</UL><P>
With the abdication of leadership in the war on drugs, public resolve has been eroded.  Conflicting messages about the acceptability of drug use have left American children more open and more vulnerable to drug use than ever before.</blockquote></td></tr>
</TABLE>
<P>
</BODY>
