<html>
<head>
<title>October Briefly Noted</title>
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="O" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/bn/bn.gif"><br>
</center>
<h2>Briefly Noted</h2>
<h3>November 1996</h3>
<br>
<p>
The JOYCE FOUNDATION has awarded $179,455 to the AMERICAN FRIENDS SERVICE COMMITTEE, which will use the 
money to &quot;work with a group of midwestern Catholic dioceses to organize a year-long grassroots education and action campaign 
centered around money and politics.&quot;  The project, &quot;Dollars and Democracy: The Search for the Common Good,&quot; will bring citizens in 
various cities together to examine &quot;how private money shapes public decision-making.&quot;
<HR>
<P>
<P>The Joyce Foundation's September newsletter notes that &quot;Today religious groups have a strong political presence, and a 
majority of Americans think that's the way it should be.&quot;  The article notes that a May 1996 poll by the PEW RESEARCH CENTER 
FOR PEOPLE AND THE PRESS revealed that 54 percent said churches should speak out on public issues  which is almost 
exactly the reverse of a 1968 poll where 53 percent said churches should avoid politics.
<hr>
<P>
<P>The California Attorney General's office is investigating whether the CALIFORNIA WELLNESS FOUNDATION violated its 
charter by funding an opinion poll on the California Civil Rights Initiative (Prop. 209).  The Foundation, which is supposed to promote 
health, spent $102,000 on a survey to access the potential health care impact of banning preferences and set-asides.  If the state 
finds that a violation occurred, board members could be personally responsible for repaying the Foundation.  
[<I>Los Angeles Times</I>]
<HR>
<P>
<P>A recent HERITAGE FOUNDATION study, entitled &quot;From Meany to Sweeney: Labor's Leftward Tilt,&quot; documents labor unions' 
ties to various far-left interest groups like the DEMOCRATIC SOCIALISTS OF AMERICA (of which AFL-CIO President John 
Sweeney is a member), EMILY'S LIST, and PEOPLE FOR THE AMERICAN WAY.  The report, authored by Kenneth Weinstein and 
August Stofferahn, notes that the AFL-CIO has attacked groups like the Christian Coalition, Focus on the Family, and the American 
Family Association as &quot;religious extremists [who] pose a significant threat to those candidates who would best represent 
America's working families.&quot;
<HR>
<P>
<P>No sooner had the Virginia Military Institute announced its decision to admit women next year, then the 
NATIONAL ORGANIZATION FOR WOMEN denounced VMI's plan to make female cadets meet the same physical training standards as men. 
 &quot;VMI is obviously lamenting the downfall of the phallocracy,&quot; cried NOW Vice President Karen Johnson.  So much for equality.
<HR>
<P>
<P>The Archdiocese of Oklahoma City has sold all of its stock in the WALT DISNEY CORPORATION, citing the movie &quot;Priest&quot; 
and an exhibit at Disney World as its main objections.  A spokesman for the archdiocese said that Disney's actions have 
become &quot;morally reprehensible as well as antithetical to the values they formerly professed.&quot;  The film &quot;Priest&quot; was condemned by 
many, including the CATHOLIC LEAGUE FOR RELIGIOUS AND CIVIL RIGHTS, for its extremely negative portrayal of Catholic 
clergy. [<I>Catholic News Service</I>]
<HR>
<P>
<P>Contributions to the federal government's workplace giving program, the COMBINED FEDERAL CAMPAIGN, have been falling. 
 Donations have fallen from over $204 million in 1991 to $189 million last year, with just over 40 percent of employees participating. 
 Focus group surveys attribute the lack of support to federal downsizing and government shut-downs.  
[<I>Washington Post</I>]
<HR>
<P>
<P>As part of its Project Change anti-racism initiative, the LEVI STRAUSS FOUNDATION announced it was awarding $300,000 
to six &quot;social justice organizations.&quot;  The recipients are the NATIONAL COUNCIL OF CHURCHES, the CENTER 
FOR CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHTS, the CENTER FOR DEMOCRATIC RENEWAL AND EDUCATION, the LEADERSHIP 
CONFERENCE EDUCATION FUND, the NATIONAL CONFERENCE, and the SIMON WIESENTHAL CENTER.
<HR>
<P>
<P>The Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals has ruled that the interest collected on client trust accounts (IOLTAs) is client property, 
raising the possibility that such funds may not be pooled together and distributed to activist groups, as is currently the practice in 
most states.  IOLTAs are a key source of funds for litigious interest groups.  According to the WASHINGTON LEGAL 
FOUNDATION, they constitute an unconstitutional taking of property without compensation.<HR>
</BODY>
