<head>
<title>The New York Times EDITORIALS/LETTERS thursday, august 10, 1995</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><h2><i>The New York Times</i> EDITORIALS/LETTERS<br>
Thursday, August 10, 1995</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<h3>Gift to TV Networks</h3>
<br>
To the Editor:<p>
Re "Media Mergers" (editorial, Aug. 2): Under pressure from the television networks,
Congress and the Federal Communications Commission will soon reward these
megacorporations with a multibillion-dollar deal to double their share of the airwaves free.  The broadcasters were to use this spectrum for the transition to high-definition television.  However, they are reneging on that deal -- to provide more "quality" television.  They will also use the airwaves for paging, and voice and data services.<p>
Recent auctions of public airwaves raised $10 billion to reduce the deficit; if these
companies paid billions, why shouldn't Disney, Group W and Rupert Murdoch?  The giveaway is valued at $10 billion to $100 billion.  Unless Congress reverses course, the taxpayer will pay.<p>
Karen Kerrigan<br>
President<br>
Small Business Survival Committee<br>
Washington, August 7, 1995<br>
<br>
[ <a href="home.html">Home</a> ]
</body>
